[src:deno-deploy/deno-software] Deno explicitly takes on the role of both runtime and package manager within a single executable, rather than requiring a separate package-management program.
[src:deno-deploy/deno-software] Deno was announced at JSConf EU 2018 by Ryan Dahl in his talk "10 Things I Regret About Node.js".
[src:deno-deploy/deno-software] He eventually presented the prototype of Deno, aiming to achieve system call bindings through message passing with serialization tools such as Protocol Buffers, and to provide command line flags for access control.
[src:deno-deploy/deno-software] Deno was initially written in Go and used Protocol Buffers for serialization between privileged (Go, with system call access) and unprivileged (V8) sides.
[src:deno-deploy/deno-software] However, Go was soon replaced with Rust due to concerns of double runtime and garbage collection pressure.
[src:deno-deploy/deno-software] A standard library, modeled after Go's standard library, was created in November 2018 to provide extensive tools and utilities, partially solving Node.js' dependency tree explosion problem.
[src:deno-deploy/deno-software] The official Deno 1.0 was released on May 13, 2020.
[src:deno-deploy/deno-software] Deno Deploy, inspired by Cloudflare Workers, was released on June 23, 2021.
[src:deno-deploy/deno-software] Announced May 4, 2022 Beta 4 improved the dashboard and added billing functionality.
[src:deno-deploy/deno-software] Deno Fresh 1.0 was announced June 28, 2022.
[src:deno-deploy/deno-software] It features a new full stack web framework for Deno that by default sends zero JavaScript to the client.
[src:deno-deploy/deno-software] The framework has no build step which allows for an order of magnitude improvements in deployment times.
[src:deno-deploy/deno-software] Version 1.1 was released September 8, 2022.
[src:deno-deploy/deno-software] Deno SaaSKit beta was announced April 4, 2023.
[src:deno-deploy/deno-software] It is an open-source, modern SaaS template built with Fresh and Deno.
[src:deno-deploy/deno-software] It primarily brings Node.js compatibility improvements and removes deprecated features.
[src:deno-deploy/deno-software] Deno aims to be a productive and secure scripting environment for the modern programmer.
[src:deno-deploy/deno-software] Similar to Node.js, Deno emphasizes event-driven architecture, providing a set of non-blocking core I/O utilities, along with their blocking versions.
[src:deno-deploy/deno-software] Deno could be used to create web servers, perform scientific computations, etc.
[src:deno-deploy/deno-software] Deno is open source software under the MIT License.
[src:deno-deploy/deno-software] Deno and Node.js are both runtimes built on the V8 JavaScript engine developed by the Chromium Project, the engine used for Chromium and Google Chrome web browsers.
[src:deno-deploy/deno-software] They both have internal event loops and provide command-line interfaces for running scripts and a wide range of system utilities.
[src:deno-deploy/deno-software] Supports URLs for loading local or remote dependencies, similar to browsers, and uses module specifiers like `npm:` and `node:` to import NPM or polyfill Node.JS modules.
[src:deno-deploy/deno-software] Does not require a package manager for resource fetching, thus no need for a registry like npm.
[src:deno-deploy/deno-software] Supports TypeScript out of the box, using a snapshotted TypeScript compiler or the swc compiler with caching mechanisms.
[src:deno-deploy/deno-software] Aims for better compatibility with browsers with a wide range of Web APIs.
[src:deno-deploy/deno-software] Restricts file system and network access by default in order to run sandboxed code.
[src:deno-deploy/deno-software] Supports a single API to utilize promises, ES6 and TypeScript features whereas Node.js supports both promise and callback APIs.
[src:deno-deploy/deno-software] Minimizes core API size, while providing a large standard library with no external dependencies.
[src:deno-deploy/deno-software] Uses message passing channels for invoking privileged system APIs and using bindings.
[src:deno-deploy/deno-software] On March 29, 2021, Deno Land Inc was announced, with backing in millions of dollars from Shasta Ventures, Mozilla Corporation and a few others.
[src:deno-deploy/deno-software] It was established to further the development of Deno and provide a commercial offering to users.
[src:deno-deploy/deno-software] A year on, Deno announced a further $21 million in Series A funding led by Sequoia Capital.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] The term began being used in the 1990s to describe content delivery networks—these were used to deliver website and video content from servers located near users.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] In the early 2000s, these systems expanded their scope to hosting other applications, leading to early edge computing services.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] These services could do things like find dealers, manage shopping carts, gather real-time data, and place ads.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] The Internet of things (IoT), where devices are connected to the Internet, is often linked with edge computing.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] Edge computing involves running computer programs that deliver quick responses close to where requests are made.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] Karim Arabi, during an IEEE DAC 2014 keynote and later at an MIT MTL Seminar in 2015, described edge computing as computing that occurs outside the cloud, at the network's edge, particularly for applications needing immediate data processing.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] Edge computing is often equated with fog computing, particularly in smaller setups.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] However, in larger deployments, such as smart cities, fog computing serves as a distinct layer between edge computing and cloud computing, with each layer having its own responsibilities.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] "The State of the Edge" report explains that edge computing focuses on servers located close to the end-users.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] Alex Reznik, Chair of the ETSI MEC ISG standards committee, defines 'edge' loosely as anything that's not a traditional data center.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] In cloud gaming, edge nodes, known as "gamelets", are typically within one or two network hops from the client, ensuring quick response times for real-time games.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] Edge computing might use virtualization technology to simplify deploying and managing various applications on edge servers.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] In 2018, the world's data was expected to grow 61 percent to 175 zettabytes by 2025.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] According to research firm Gartner, around 10 percent of enterprise-generated data is created and processed outside a traditional centralized data center or cloud.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] By 2025, the firm predicts that this figure will reach 75 percent.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] The increase in IoT devices at the edge of the network is producing a massive amount of data — storing and using all that data in cloud data centers pushes network bandwidth requirements to the limit.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] Despite the improvements in network technology, data centers cannot guarantee acceptable transfer rates and response times, which often is a critical requirement for many applications.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] Furthermore, devices at the edge constantly consume data coming from the cloud, forcing companies to decentralize data storage and service provisioning, leveraging physical proximity to the end user.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] In a similar way, the aim of edge computing is to move the computation away from data centers towards the edge of the network, exploiting smart objects, mobile phones, or network gateways to perform tasks and provide services on behalf of the cloud.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] By moving services to the edge, it is possible to provide content caching, service delivery, persistent data storage, and IoT management resulting in better response times and transfer rates.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] At the same time, distributing the logic to different network nodes introduces new issues and challenges.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] The distributed nature of this paradigm introduces a shift in security schemes used in cloud computing.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] In edge computing, data may travel between different distributed nodes connected via the internet, and thus requires special encryption mechanisms independent of the cloud.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] This approach minimizes latency, reduces bandwidth consumption, and enhances real-time responsiveness for applications.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] Edge nodes may also be resource-constrained devices, limiting the choice in terms of security methods.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] Moreover, a shift from centralized top-down infrastructure to a decentralized trust model is required.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] On the other hand, by keeping and processing data at the edge, it is possible to increase privacy by minimizing the transmission of sensitive information to the cloud.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] Furthermore, the ownership of collected data shifts from service providers to end-users.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] Scalability in a distributed network must face different issues.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] First, it must take into account the heterogeneity of the devices, having different performance and energy constraints, the highly dynamic condition, and the reliability of the connections compared to more robust infrastructure of cloud data centers.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] Moreover, security requirements may introduce further latency in the communication between nodes, which may slow down the scaling process.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] The state-of-the-art scheduling technique can increase the effective utilization of edge resources and scales the edge server by assigning minimum edge resources to each offloaded task.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] Management of failovers is crucial in order to keep a service alive.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] If a single node goes down and is unreachable, users should still be able to access a service without interruptions.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] Moreover, edge computing systems must provide actions to recover from a failure and alert the user about the incident.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] To this aim, each device must maintain the network topology of the entire distributed system, so that detection of errors and recovery become easily applicable.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] Other factors that may influence this aspect are the connection technologies in use, which may provide different levels of reliability, and the accuracy of the data produced at the edge that could be unreliable due to particular environment conditions.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] As an example, an edge computing device, such as a voice assistant, may continue to provide service to local users even during cloud service or internet outages.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] Edge computing brings analytical computational resources close to the end users and therefore can increase the responsiveness and throughput of applications.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] A well-designed edge platform would significantly outperform a traditional cloud-based system.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] Some applications rely on short response times, making edge computing a significantly more feasible option than cloud computing.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] Examples range from IoT to autonomous driving, anything health or human / public safety relevant, or involving human perception such as facial recognition, which typically takes a human between 370-620 ms to perform.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] Edge computing is more likely to be able to mimic the same perception speed as humans, which is useful in applications such as augmented reality, where the headset should preferably recognize who a person is at the same time as the wearer does.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] Due to the nearness of the analytical resources to the end users, sophisticated analytical tools and artificial intelligence tools can run on the edge of the system.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] This placement at the edge helps to increase operational efficiency and is responsible for many advantages to the system.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] In distributed AI systems on the edge, data compression is increasingly recognized as a foundational design layer to mitigate bandwidth constraints caused by the exchange of large models and high-resolution sensor streams.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] By using servers located on a local edge network to perform those computations, the video files only need to be transmitted in the local network.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] Avoiding transmission over the internet results in significant bandwidth savings and therefore increases efficiency.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] If the recognition is performed locally, it is possible to send the recognized text to the cloud rather than audio recordings, significantly reducing the amount of required bandwidth.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] Edge application services reduce the volumes of data that must be moved, the consequent traffic, and the distance that data must travel.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] That provides lower latency and reduces transmission costs.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] Computation offloading for real-time applications, such as facial recognition algorithms, showed considerable improvements in response times, as demonstrated in early research.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] Further research showed that using resource-rich machines called cloudlets or micro data centers near mobile users, which offer services typically found in the cloud, provided improvements in execution time when some of the tasks are offloaded to the edge node.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] On the other hand, offloading every task may result in a slowdown due to transfer times between device and nodes, so depending on the workload, an optimal configuration can be defined.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] An IoT-based power grid system enables communication of electricity and data to monitor and control the power grid, which makes energy management more efficient.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] Other notable applications include connected cars, self-driving cars, smart cities, Industry 4.0, home automation, missiles,, satellite systems , as well as frameworks such as MediaPipe.
[src:deno-deploy/edge-computing] The growing field of **edge artificial intelligence** (edge AI or edge intelligence, sometimes referred to as "local AI" or "on-device AI") implements artificial intelligence in an edge computing environment, on the device or close to where data is collected.
[src:deno-deploy/javascript-engine] The first JavaScript engines were interpreters of the source code, but modern engines use just-in-time compilation to improve performance.
[src:deno-deploy/javascript-engine] JavaScript engines are typically developed by web browser vendors, and every major browser includes one.
[src:deno-deploy/javascript-engine] In a browser, the JavaScript engine runs in concert with the rendering engine via the Document Object Model and Web IDL bindings.
[src:deno-deploy/javascript-engine] However, the use of JavaScript engines is not limited to browsers; For example, the V8 engine is a core component of the Node.js runtime system.
[src:deno-deploy/javascript-engine] They are also called ECMAScript engines, after the official name of the specification.
[src:deno-deploy/javascript-engine] With the advent of WebAssembly, some engines can also execute this code in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:deno-deploy/javascript-engine] The first JavaScript engine was created by Brendan Eich in 1995 for the Netscape Navigator web browser.
[src:deno-deploy/javascript-engine] It was a rudimentary interpreter for the nascent language Eich invented.
[src:deno-deploy/javascript-engine] Google debuted its Chrome browser in 2008, introducing the V8 JavaScript engine that was at the time much faster than its competition.
[src:deno-deploy/javascript-engine] This sparked a race between browser vendors to deliver ever-faster JavaScript engines.
[src:deno-deploy/javascript-engine] The key innovations around this era were switching from basic tree-walking interpreters to stack- and register-based bytecode VM interpreters, just-in-time compilation (JIT), inline caching (hidden classes) and generational GC.
[src:deno-deploy/javascript-engine] Apple released the JIT-enabled Nitro engine in June 2008 for its Safari browser, which had 30% better performance than its predecessor.
[src:deno-deploy/javascript-engine] Mozilla followed suit in August 2008 with TraceMonkey, the first JIT compiler for SpiderMonkey engine, released in Firefox 3.1.
[src:deno-deploy/javascript-engine] Opera joined the performance race with their register-bytecode based and JIT-enabled Carakan engine, 2009 and released in April 2010.
[src:deno-deploy/javascript-engine] Microsoft's first JIT-enabled Chakra engine, in development since 2008, debuted as part of Internet Explorer 9 in 2011.
[src:deno-deploy/javascript-engine] Its major rewrite appeared in Microsoft Edge Legacy in 2015 and open-sourced as ChakraCore in 2016.
[src:deno-deploy/javascript-engine] Further performance gains in major JavaScript engines were later achieved with the introduction of multi-tiered JIT architectures.
[src:deno-deploy/javascript-engine] Progressively advanced JIT compilers are used to optimize hotspots in user code, with each next tier delivering ever more performant native code at the cost of slower compile time.
[src:deno-deploy/javascript-engine] Chrome was the first to implement it in V8 in 2010 with the introduction of Crankshaft, a 2-tiered JIT compiler.
[src:deno-deploy/javascript-engine] By 2023, architecture of V8 evolved into 4 tiers: Ignition – register-based bytecode interpreter, Sparkplug – a fast non-optimizing JIT compiler, Maglev and TurboFan – slower optimizing JIT compilers.
[src:deno-deploy/javascript-engine] JavaScriptCore today has a similar 4-tier architecture, while Firefox's SpiderMonkey and ChakraCore have 3 tiers (interpreter and 2-tiered JIT).
[src:deno-deploy/javascript-engine] V8's influence expanded beyond browsers with the release of Node.js in 2009 and its package manager npm in 2010.
[src:deno-deploy/javascript-engine] As their popularity exploded, V8 also became the engine powering vast amounts of server-side JavaScript code.
[src:deno-deploy/javascript-engine] In 2013, Electron framework appeared that let developers create desktop apps with web technologies as well, using Chromium with V8 and Node.js under the hood.
[src:deno-deploy/javascript-engine] Eventually asm.js and NaCl (a competing Google's technology) evolved into WebAssembly standard in 2017, with all major engines adding support for it.
[src:deno-deploy/javascript-engine] The six-year gap between ECMAScript 5 (2009) and ES6 (2015) marked a major inflection point for JavaScript engine development.
[src:deno-deploy/javascript-engine] Whereas ES5 was a relatively compact language with straightforward basic implementation, ES6 introduced foundations of modern JavaScript, with substantially increased complexity, as well as an annual release cycle for new specification versions.
[src:deno-deploy/javascript-engine] This put the focus not only on performance optimization, but also on keeping pace with the rapidly evolving standards (of both ECMAScript and wider web ecosystem) and led to a consolidation around engines that had the resources to do it.
[src:deno-deploy/javascript-engine] Many smaller projects did not end up fully implementing ES6 spec, and Opera and Microsoft both ceased developing their engines and adopted V8 in 2013 and 2021.
[src:deno-deploy/javascript-engine] Nashorn engine was dropped from OpenJDK over a similar concern about ECMAScript's rapid development.
[src:deno-deploy/javascript-engine] These engines have been discontinued and are mostly interesting for the historical perspective.
[src:deno-deploy/javascript-engine] Some may still be in use today for legacy purposes (especially Microsoft's old engines that continue to ship with Windows).
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] TypeScript may be used to develop JavaScript applications for both client-side and server-side execution (as with React.js, Node.js, Deno or Bun).
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] Multiple options are available for transpiling.
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] The default TypeScript Compiler can be used, or the Babel compiler can be invoked to convert TypeScript to JavaScript.
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] TypeScript supports definition files that can contain type information of existing JavaScript libraries, much like C++ header files can describe the structure of existing object files.
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] This enables other programs to use the values defined in the files as if they were statically typed TypeScript entities.
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] There are third-party header files for popular libraries such as jQuery, MongoDB, and D3.js.
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] TypeScript headers for the Node.js library modules are also available, allowing development of Node.js programs within TypeScript.
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] The TypeScript compiler is written in TypeScript and compiled to JavaScript.
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] It is licensed under the Apache License 2.0.
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] Anders Hejlsberg, lead architect of C# and creator of Delphi and Turbo Pascal, has worked on developing TypeScript.
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] TypeScript was released to the public in October 2012, with version 0.8, after two years of internal development at Microsoft.
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] Soon after the initial public release, Miguel de Icaza praised the language, but criticized the lack of mature integrated development environment (IDE) support apart from Microsoft Visual Studio, which was unavailable then on Linux and macOS.
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] As of April 2021 there is support in other IDEs and text editors, including Emacs, Vim, WebStorm, Atom and Microsoft's own Visual Studio Code.
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] TypeScript 0.9, released in 2013, added support for generics.
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] TypeScript 1.0 was released at Microsoft's Build developer conference in 2014.
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] Visual Studio 2013 Update 2 provided built-in support for TypeScript.
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] Further improvement were made in July 2014, when the development team announced a new TypeScript compiler, asserted to have a five-fold performance increase.
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] Simultaneously, the source code, which was initially hosted on CodePlex, was moved to GitHub.
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] On 22 September 2016, TypeScript 2.0 was released, introducing several features, including the ability for programmers to optionally enforce null safety.
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] TypeScript 3.0 was released on 30 July 2018, bringing many language additions like tuples in rest parameters and spread expressions, rest parameters with tuple types, generic rest parameters and so on.
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] TypeScript 4.0 was released on 20 August 2020.
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] While 4.0 did not introduce any breaking changes, it added language features such as Custom JSX Factories and Variadic Tuple Types.
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] TypeScript 5.0 was released on 16 March 2023 and included support for decorators.
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] On March 11, 2025, Anders Hejlsberg announced on the TypeScript blog that the team is working on a Go port of the TypeScript compiler to be released as TypeScript version 7.0 later this year.
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] It is expected to feature a 10x speedup.
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] On December 2nd, 2025, Daniel Rosenwasser announced on the blog that TypeScript 6.0 will be the last release written in TypeScript itself, and TypeScript 7.0 will be the first Go-based release.
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] TypeScript originated from the shortcomings of JavaScript for developing large-scale applications both at Microsoft and among their external customers.
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] Challenges with dealing with complex JavaScript code led to demand for custom tooling to ease developing of components in the language.
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] Developers sought a solution that would not break compatibility with the ECMAScript (ES) standard and its ecosystem, so a compiler was developed to transform a superset of JavaScript with type annotations and classes (TypeScript files) back into vanilla ECMAScript 5 code.
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] TypeScript classes were based on the then-proposed ECMAScript 6 class specification to make writing prototypal inheritance less verbose and error-prone, and type annotations enabled IntelliSense and improved tooling.
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] Syntactically, TypeScript is very similar to JScript .NET, another Microsoft implementation of the ECMA-262 language standard that added support for static typing and classical object-oriented language features such as classes, inheritance, interfaces, and namespaces.
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] As TypeScript is simply a superset of JavaScript, existing JavaScript can be adapted to TypeScript and TypeScript program can seamlessly consume JavaScript.
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] The compiler can target all ECMAScript versions 5 and above, transpiling modern features like classes and arrow functions to their older counterparts.
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] With TypeScript, it is possible to use existing JavaScript code, incorporate popular JavaScript libraries, and call TypeScript-generated code from other JavaScript.
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] Type declarations for these libraries are usually provided with the source code but can be declared or installed separately if needed.
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] The TypeScript compiler, named `tsc`, is written in TypeScript.
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] As a result, it can be compiled into regular JavaScript and can then be executed in any JavaScript engine (e.g. a browser).
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] The compiler package comes bundled with a script host that can execute the compiler.
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] It is also available as a Node.js package that uses Node.js as a host.
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] The compiler is currently being rewritten in Go for version 7.
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] The compiler can *target* a given edition of ECMAScript (such as ECMAScript 5 for legacy browser compatibility), but by default compiles for the latest standards.
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] Using plug-ins, TypeScript can be integrated with build automation tools, including Grunt (grunt-ts), Apache Maven (TypeScript Maven Plugin), Gulp (gulp-typescript) and Gradle (TypeScript Gradle Plugin).
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] TSLint scans TypeScript code for conformance to a set of standards and guidelines.
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] ESLint, a standard JavaScript linter, also provided some support for TypeScript via community plugins.
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] However, ESLint's inability to leverage TypeScript's language services precluded certain forms of semantic linting and program-wide analysis.
[src:deno-deploy/typescript] In early 2019, the TSLint team announced the linter's deprecation in favor of `typescript-eslint`, a joint effort of the TSLint, ESLint and TypeScript teams to consolidate linting under the ESLint umbrella for improved performance, community unity and developer accessibility.
[src:deno-deploy/v8-javascript-engine] Google created V8 for its Chrome browser, so V8's first release coincided with Chrome's first release in 2008.
[src:deno-deploy/v8-javascript-engine] It was named after the V8 engine, and its lead developer was Lars Bak.
[src:deno-deploy/v8-javascript-engine] For several years, Chrome was faster than other browsers at executing JavaScript.
[src:deno-deploy/v8-javascript-engine] The V8 assembler is based on the Strongtalk assembler.
[src:deno-deploy/v8-javascript-engine] On 7 December 2010, a new compiling infrastructure named Crankshaft was released, with speed improvements.
[src:deno-deploy/v8-javascript-engine] In version 41 of Chrome in 2015, project TurboFan was added to provide more performance improvements with previously challenging workloads such as asm.js.
[src:deno-deploy/v8-javascript-engine] Much of V8's development is strongly inspired by the Java HotSpot Virtual Machine developed by Sun Microsystems, with the newer execution pipelines being very similar to those of HotSpot's.
[src:deno-deploy/v8-javascript-engine] Support for the WebAssembly language began in 2015.
[src:deno-deploy/v8-javascript-engine] In 2016, the Ignition interpreter was added to V8 with the design goal of reducing the memory usage on small memory Android phones in comparison with TurboFan and Crankshaft.
[src:deno-deploy/v8-javascript-engine] Ignition is a register based machine and shares a similar (albeit not the exact same) design to the templating interpreter utilized by HotSpot.
[src:deno-deploy/v8-javascript-engine] In 2017, V8 shipped a brand-new compiler pipeline, consisting of Ignition (the interpreter) and TurboFan (the optimizing compiler).
[src:deno-deploy/v8-javascript-engine] Starting with V8 version 5.9, Full-codegen (the early baseline compiler) and Crankshaft are no longer used in V8 for JavaScript execution, since the team believed they were no longer able to keep pace with new JavaScript language features and the optimizations those features required.
[src:deno-deploy/v8-javascript-engine] In 2021, a new tiered compilation pipeline was introduced with the release of the SparkPlug compiler, which supplements the existing TurboFan compiler within V8, in a direct parallel to the profiling C1 Compiler used by HotSpot.
[src:deno-deploy/v8-javascript-engine] V8 first generates an abstract syntax tree with its own parser.
[src:deno-deploy/v8-javascript-engine] Then, Ignition generates bytecode from this syntax tree using the internal V8 bytecode format.
[src:deno-deploy/v8-javascript-engine] TurboFan compiles this bytecode into machine code.
[src:deno-deploy/v8-javascript-engine] In other words, V8 compiles ECMAScript directly to native machine code using just-in-time compilation before executing it.
[src:deno-deploy/v8-javascript-engine] The compiled code is additionally optimized (and re-optimized) dynamically at runtime, based on heuristics of the code's execution profile.
[src:deno-deploy/v8-javascript-engine] Optimization techniques used include inlining, elision of expensive runtime properties, and inline caching.
[src:deno-deploy/v8-javascript-engine] The garbage collector is a generational incremental collector.
[src:deno-deploy/v8-javascript-engine] V8 can compile to x86, ARM or MIPS instruction set architectures in both their 32-bit and 64-bit editions; it has additionally been ported to PowerPC, and to IBM ESA/390 and z/Architecture, for use in servers.
[src:deno-deploy/v8-javascript-engine] V8 can be used in a browser or integrated into independent projects.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] The main goal of WebAssembly is to facilitate high-performance applications on web pages, but it is also designed to be usable in non-web environments.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] It is an open standard intended to support any language on any operating system, and in practice many of the most popular languages already have at least some level of support.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] Announced in 2015 (2015) and first released in March 2017 (2017-03), WebAssembly became a World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) recommendation on 5 December 2019 and it received the *Programming Languages Software Award* from the Association for Computing Machinery (ACM) SIGPLAN in 2021.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] The W3C maintains the standard with contributions from Mozilla, Microsoft, Google, Apple, Fastly, Intel, and Red Hat.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] The name "WebAssembly" is intended to suggest bringing assembly language programming to the World Wide Web, where it will be executed client-side, by the website-user's computer via the user's web browser.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] To accomplish this, WebAssembly must be much more hardware-independent than a true assembly language.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] WebAssembly was first announced in 2015, and the first demonstration was executing Unity's *Angry Bots* in Firefox, Google Chrome, and Microsoft Edge [Legacy].
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] The precursor technologies were asm.js from Mozilla and Google Native Client, and the initial implementation was based on the feature set of asm.js.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] In March 2017, the design of the minimum viable product (MVP) was declared to be finished and the preview phase ended.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] In late September 2017, Safari 11 was released with support.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] In February 2018, the WebAssembly Working Group published three public working drafts for the Core Specification, JavaScript Interface, and Web API.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] The MVP was focused on low-level languages such as C and C++, with the intent to add features useful for high-level languages in a future version.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] The WebAssembly 2.0 specification was finished in 2022 and became a W3C standard in December 2024.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] It adds many single instruction, multiple data (SIMD) related instructions and a new v128 datatype, with the ability for functions to return multiple values, mass memory initialize/copy instructions, and reference types, which are opaque pointers to objects outside of the linear memory.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] WebAssembly 3.0 was released in September 2025.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] New features include a 64-bit address space, multiple address spaces, exception handling, and garbage collected struct and array types.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] Support for garbage collection enables more efficient compiling for high-level languages, but WasmGC from WebAssembly 3.0 lacks the abilities needed by .NET runtime.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] While WebAssembly was initially designed to permit near-native code execution speed in the web browser, it has been considered valuable outside of such, in more generalized contexts.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] A WebAssembly runtime environment is a low-level virtual stack machine, akin to JVM or Flash VM; it can be embedded into any host application, and thus there have been created standalone WebAssembly runtime environments, including Wasmtime , WebAssembly Micro Runtime , Wasmer , WasmEdge and wazero .
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] In November 2017, Mozilla declared support "in all major browsers", after WebAssembly was enabled by default in Edge [Legacy] 16.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] This support also includes mobile web browsers for iOS and Android.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] As of March 2024, 99% of tracked web browsers support WebAssembly (version 1.0), more than for its predecessor asm.js.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] For some extensions, from the 2.0 draft standard, support may be lower, but still more than 90% of web browsers may already support, e.g. the reference types extension.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] Non-browser WebAssembly runtimes include Wasmer, Wasmtime, WAMR, WAVM, wasm3, and others.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] These systems execute precompiled Wasm modules and often provide additional APIs for embedding WebAssembly in different environments.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] Use cases for wasm outside the browser include plug-in interfaces and lightweight virtualization.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] WebAssembly implementations generally use either ahead-of-time (AOT) or just-in-time (JIT) compiling, though some may also use an interpreter.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] While the first implementations appeared in web browsers, there are now many non-browser implementations for general-purpose use.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] Because WebAssembly executables are precompiled, a variety of programming languages can target Wasm.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] Compiling is done either through direct output to Wasm or via intermediate virtual machines implemented in Wasm.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] As of 2021, around 40 programming languages support WebAssembly as a compiling target.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] Web browsers prevent WebAssembly code from directly manipulating the Document Object Model.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] Wasm code must defer to JavaScript for this.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] In an October 2023 survey of developers, less than half of the 303 participants were satisfied with the state of WebAssembly.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] A large majority cited the need for improvement in four areas: § WASI, debugging support, integration with JavaScript and browser APIs, and build tooling.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] All major browsers allow WebAssembly if `Content-Security-Policy` is not specified, or if the value `unsafe-eval` is used, but behave differently otherwise; Chrome *requires* `unsafe-eval`, though a worker thread can be a workaround.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] In June 2018, a security researcher presented the possibility of using WebAssembly to circumvent browser mitigations for Spectre and Meltdown security vulnerabilities once support for threads with shared memory is added.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] Due to this concern, WebAssembly developers put the feature on hold.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] However, in order to explore these future language extensions, Google Chrome added experimental support for the WebAssembly thread proposal in October 2018.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] WebAssembly has been criticized for allowing greater ease of hiding the evidence for malware writers, scammers and phishing attackers; WebAssembly is present on the user's machine only in its compiled form, which "[makes malware] detection difficult".
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] Speed and the easy ability to conceal in WebAssembly have led to its use in hidden crypto mining within the website visitor's device.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] An April 2021 study from Universität Stuttgart found that since then crypto mining has been marginalized, falling to below 1% of all WebAssembly modules gathered from a wide range of sources, also including the Alexa top 1 million websites.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] As WebAssembly supports only structured control flow, it is amenable toward security verification techniques including symbolic execution.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] In 2019, a group of researchers from the University of Massachusetts Amherst presented a comprehensive analysis of WebAssembly's performance compared to native code.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] The paper identified several reasons for this performance difference, including missing optimizations, code generation issues in WebAssembly compilers, and inherent limits of the WebAssembly platform.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] In 2022, it was determined by researchers that a Wasm program runs at about 120% of (or 20% faster than) the speed of a comparable JavaScript program.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] Those findings align with the experience of a startup company named "Zaplib", whose founders summarized in a blog that it was shutting down due to lack of performance in WebAssembly.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] Their goal had been to significantly increase the performance of existing web apps by incrementally porting them to Rust/Wasm; however, porting a customer's simulator from JavaScript yielded only a 5% improvement in performance.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] Benchmarking has revealed several other pain-points for WebAssembly, such as poor performance because of no direct access to the DOM, a problem which is being addressed.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] WebAssembly System Interface (WASI) is a simple interface (application binary interface (ABI) and application programming interface (API)) designed by Mozilla, which is intended to be portable to any platform.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] It provides features similar to the Portable Operating System Interface (POSIX), such as file input/output (I/O) constrained by capability-based security.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] WASI is influenced by CloudABI and Capsicum.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] Solomon Hykes, a co-founder of Docker, wrote in 2019, "If WASM+WASI existed in 2008, we wouldn't have needed to create Docker.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] WASI 0.1 provides a few POSIX-like APIs such as file I/O, reading environment variables, and random-number generation, but has very little support for networking.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] WASI 0.2 is redesigned based on the WebAssembly Component Model.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] WASI 0.3 will add support for async functions; the host translates between blocking and async function calls, so an exported function that blocks may be called as an asynchronous function, and vice-versa.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] Starting in 0.2, WASI is defined in terms of the component model.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] Interfaces in the component model are specified in an IDL called WIT (WebAssembly Interface Types).
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] While core wasm only supports integer and floating-point numbers, interfaces in WIT can express types such as strings, lists, and user-defined record and variant types, and are language-agnostic.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] Components cannot access each other's memory, and so interact only via imported and exported functions.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] The component model is designed around composition: two components can be composed into a single component when the exports of one component match another's imports, allowing any interface to be virtualized.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] Interfaces in WIT are grouped together into a "world".
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] WASI 0.2 defines a CLI world similar to the POSIX-like API of WASI 0.1, and an HTTP proxy world for web servers.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] The component model is not currently supported by browsers.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] The general standard provides core specifications for the JavaScript API and details on embedding.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] Wasm code (binary code, i.e. bytecode) is intended to be run on a portable virtual stack machine (VM).
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] The VM is designed to be faster to parse and execute than JavaScript and to have compact code representation.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] Any external functionality (like syscalls) that may be expected by Wasm binary code is not stipulated by the standard; instead, the standard specifies how the host environment can provide such an interface via a "module".
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] A Wasm program is designed as a separate module containing collections of various Wasm-defined values and program type definitions.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] These are provided in either binary or textual format (see below) that have a common structure.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] Such a module may provide a start function that is executed upon instantiation of a wasm binary.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] The list of instruction types includes those for standard memory load/store, numeric, parametric, control flow, and Wasm-specific variables.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] The number of opcodes used in the original standard (§ MVP) was a bit fewer than 200 of the 256 possible opcodes.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] Subsequent versions of WebAssembly pushed the number of opcodes a bit over 200.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] The WebAssembly SIMD proposal (for parallel processing) introduces an alternate opcode prefix (0xfd) for 128-bit wide SIMD instructions; the concatenation of the SIMD prefix, plus an opcode that is valid after the SIMD prefix, forms each SIMD opcode.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] These SIMD opcodes are both portable and intended to map directly to native instruction sets like x86-64 and ARM.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] In contrast, SIMD instructions are not directly supported by Java's JVM or .NET's CIL; however, both do have some APIs for parallel processing, which provide SIMD speedups.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] A newer set of "relaxed SIMD" instructions allow for a limited amount of implementation-defined behavior to improve performance.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] In March 2017, the WebAssembly Community Group reached consensus on the initial ("MVP") binary format, JavaScript API, and reference interpreter.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] It defines a WebAssembly binary format (`.wasm`), which is designed to be used by computers, not humans, and a text format that is human-readable (`.wat`), resembling a cross between S-expressions and traditional assembly languages.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] The binary format is straightforward and designed to allow streaming compiling, so compiling can begin before the module is finished downloading, and to allow functions to be compiled in parallel.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] All integer constants are encoded using a space-efficient, variable-length LEB128 encoding.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] The WebAssembly text format is more canonically written in a folded format using S-expressions.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] For instructions and expressions, this format is purely syntactic sugar and has no behavioral differences with the linear format.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] A module is implicitly generated by the compiler.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] The function is referenced by an entry of the type table in the binary, hence a type section and the `type` emitted by the decompiler.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] The compiler and decompiler can be accessed online.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] Data in memory is stored in a large, growable array of bytes termed a *linear memory*.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] Linear memory is separate from the wasm module's call stack and code and the engine's memory.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] This allows running wasm code in the same process as the JavaScript virtual machine it's embedded in without violating memory safety.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] A module contains a list of global variables separate from linear memory, which may be mutable or immutable.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] Functions declare a list of local variables.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] A function's parameters are also local variables.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] Instructions operate on a stack of values.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] The stack layout is fixed (branches must push and pop the same number of operands), so wasm engines can compile the stack away, producing efficient machine code operations on registers, rather than managing a stack at runtime.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] A stack machine architecture was chosen as it can have higher code density than a register machine.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] Unlike typical assembly languages, wasm only uses structured control flow similar to high-level programming languages.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] The intentional lack of support for jump instructions makes it simple to validate and compile wasm code in a single pass, and makes it easier to read code disassembled into the text format.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] Blocks are delimited with the `block`, `loop`, and `if`/`else` constructs.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] Branch instructions contain a label that identifies the depth of a block it is nested in: `br 0` will branch to the block the instruction is contained in, `br 1` will branch to the block that block is contained in, and so on.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] Branches to a `block` or `if` jump to the end of the block like a break statement, while branches to a `loop` jump back to the *beginning* of the loop, similar to a continue statement.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] The `br_table` instruction takes an input index and jumps to a target from a list of labels.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] A C-style switch statement can be expressed with a `br_table` inside a series of nested blocks.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] Compilers targeting wasm convert unstructured control flow into high-level loops using Emscripten's Relooper algorithm, originally designed to target JavaScript.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] Function declarations are listed in a separate section before the section containing the function bodies.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] Function pointers are emulated using an index into the global functions table, since code is not inside the linear memory.
[src:deno-deploy/webassembly] Functions can also be imported and exported, providing the foreign function interface to communicate with JavaScript or other embedders.
